PSA_ORIGINAL = {
  "2": {
    "7": "<p><strong>YHWH amar elai beni atta ani hayom yelidticha</strong> (<em>Yhwh ʾāmar ʾēlay, bĕnî ʾattâ ʾănî hayyôm yĕlídtîkā</em>): 'The LORD said to me: You are my Son; today I have begotten you.' The royal adoption formula of Ps 2:7 was applied to the Davidic king at his enthronement — the king became YHWH's 'son' in a representative capacity (2 Sam 7:14; Ps 89:26-27). The NT applies it to Jesus at three Christological moments: the baptism (Matt 3:17), the transfiguration (2 Pet 1:17), and the resurrection (Acts 13:33; Heb 1:5; 5:5). The resurrection is the decisive 'today' in NT usage: the day of Christ's enthronement at the Father's right hand is the day of divine sonship's full eschatological declaration.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "4": "<p><strong>mah enosh ki tizkerenu uben adam ki tipqedenu</strong> (<em>mâ-ʾĕnôš kî-tizqĕrennû ûben-ʾādām kî tipqĕdennû</em>): 'What is man that you are mindful of him, and the son of man that you care for him?' <em>Ben adam</em> (son of man) in Ps 8 is the representative human made lower than the heavenly beings and crowned with glory — a meditation on Gen 1:26-28's dominion mandate. The NT (Heb 2:5-9) applies Ps 8 to Christ as the true human who fulfills the Adamic mandate: 'We do not yet see everything in subjection to him, but we see him who for a little while was made lower than the angels, namely Jesus, crowned with glory and honor because of the suffering of death.' Christ recapitulates and fulfills humanity's Ps 8 vocation.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p><strong>eli eli lamah azavtani</strong> (<em>ʾēlî ʾēlî lāmāh ʿăzabtānî</em>): 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?' The opening of the Passion Psalm in its Hebrew form. The Aramaic at the cross (Mark 15:34: <em>Eloi eloi lema sabachthani</em>) uses the Aramaic form of the Psalm's Hebrew opening, suggesting Jesus was quoting from memory in the vernacular. The Psalm moves from dereliction (vv. 1-21) to proclamation and praise (vv. 22-31) — ending not in abandonment but in universal witness ('all the ends of the earth shall turn to the LORD', v. 27). The early church understood Jesus's citation of the Psalm's opening as invoking the whole Psalm, including its vindication ending.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p><strong>neum YHWH laadoni shev limini ad ashit oyvecha hadom leraglecha</strong> (<em>nĕʾum Yhwh laʾdōnî, šēb liymînî ʿad-ʾāšît ʾōyĕbêkā hădōm lĕraglêkā</em>): 'The oracle of YHWH to my lord: Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool.' <em>Neum</em> (oracle of) is the formula for divine speech — the highest possible speech-authority marker in Hebrew prophecy. David writes <em>laadoni</em> (to my lord), creating the theological puzzle Jesus exploits in Matt 22:41-46: how can David's descendant also be David's lord? The Davidic Messiah must be more than a Davidic son; only divine sonship accounts for the double identity. <em>Shev limini</em> (sit at my right hand): enthronement at the supreme position of divine authority — the NT applies this to the resurrection/ascension as Christ's enthronement (Acts 2:34-35; Eph 1:20-21; Heb 1:3).</p>",

    "4": "<p><strong>nishba YHWH velo yinachem atta kohen leolam al divrati malkitsedek</strong> (<em>nišbaʿ Yhwh wĕlōʾ yinnāḥēm ʾattā-kōhēn lĕʿôlām ʿal-diḇrātî malkîṣedeq</em>): 'YHWH has sworn and will not change his mind: You are a priest forever after the manner of Melchizedek.' The divine oath (<em>nishba ... velo yinachem</em>) makes this the most certain OT promise after the Abrahamic oath. <em>Malkitsedek</em> (Melchizedek, king of righteousness): the mysterious priest-king of Gen 14:18-20 who blessed Abraham and received a tithe — without genealogy, without recorded birth or death. Hebrews 7 uses the silence of Scripture about Melchizedek's origins as a typological argument: a priesthood with no recorded beginning or end points to an eternal priesthood.</p>"
  }
}

PSA_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The Psalter (150 poems spanning roughly David's reign to the post-exilic period) was the hymnbook of the Second Temple — used in liturgy from the restoration (Ezra-Nehemiah) through the NT period. The Dead Sea Scrolls (1QPs, 4QPsa-r, and 11QPsa) preserve the most psalms of any biblical book among the Qumran community, indicating the Psalter's centrality in Jewish worship. The Psalter is organized into five books (Ps 1-41, 42-72, 73-89, 90-106, 107-150) mirroring the five books of Moses, each ending with a doxology. The arrangement suggests a canonical editorial design: the Psalter tells the story of Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH from Torah-delight (Ps 1) to universal praise (Ps 150).</p>"
  },
  "62": {
    "1": "<p><b>Jeduthun</b> — the heading \"according to Jeduthun\" names a musical guild descended from one of David's three chief Levitical musicians (1 Chr 6:31-47; 16:41-42; 25:1-6). Jeduthun's guild was responsible for portions of the temple music. The heading places this psalm within the institutional liturgy of the Davidic-era worship system, not merely personal devotion. The term <i>dumiyyah</i> (silence/waiting) in the first line is a specialized word for the quiet of expectant waiting rather than mere quietude; the soul is not passive but oriented, straining toward God who has not yet acted.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>He alone is my rock and my salvation; he is my fortress</b> — the cluster of military and geological metaphors (rock, fortress, salvation) maps directly onto the Judean wilderness geography where David spent years as a fugitive. The limestone crags and fortified outcrops east of Bethlehem and around En-gedi were literal places of refuge. The \"only/alone\" (<i>ak</i>) refrain runs through the psalm six times, creating its structural spine: YHWH is the only source, making all other resources insufficient by comparison. This absolute exclusive claim is the psalm's theological core.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>How long will all of you assault a man?</b> — the psalm shifts to address the enemies directly in a manner characteristic of lament psalms. The image of a \"leaning wall\" and \"tottering fence\" describes the psalmist's political and social precariousness: not a fortress but a structure about to collapse. In the context of David's reign, this reflects the sustained court opposition he faced — from Saul's partisans, from Absalom's conspiracy, from rival factions within his own court. The enemies treat a single man as though he were a battle formation to be assaulted.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>With their mouths they bless, but inwardly they curse</b> — the double-speaking of courtiers in honor-shame cultures. ANE court culture required outward deference and praise of the powerful, but the palace intrigue documented throughout David's reign (2 Sam 15-17; 1 Kgs 1) shows that verbal blessing could conceal active plotting. The specific goal — \"to bring him down from his position\" — is political deposition from social eminence (<i>seto</i>, his height/dignity). The conspiracy is not military but social: the destruction of honor is the weapon.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>For my hope comes from him</b> — the refrain is repeated (compare v2) but the emotional word changes: from \"salvation\" (v2) to \"hope/expectation\" (<i>tiqvati</i>). Tiqvah (hope) carries the sense of expectant waiting, a cord stretched taut toward a future reality. The word is used of Rahab's scarlet cord in Josh 2:18 (the same root: a cord of hope that would preserve her). The psalmist's hope is not optimism but a taut covenant expectation that YHWH will act consistently with his character.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>I will not be shaken</b> — the refrain returns again but with a subtle strengthening: v2 says \"I will not be <i>greatly</i> shaken\" (<i>lo rabbah</i>), while v6 says simply \"I will not be shaken\" (no qualifier). The progressive stripping away of qualification mirrors the psalm's movement from realistic assessment of danger to confident trust. The Hebrew verbal forms here are imperfect — ongoing, unshakeable stability as a present and continuing posture, not a one-time declaration.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>In God rests my salvation and my honor</b> — the inclusion of <i>kavod</i> (honor/glory) alongside salvation is significant. In honor-shame culture, to be rescued but dishonored is an incomplete rescue. The enemies threatened the psalmist's <i>seto</i> (eminence, v4); YHWH's rescue must therefore include social vindication — the restoration of honor before the community that witnessed the attack. The psalm does not separate spiritual salvation from social standing because ancient Israelite life did not separate them.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Pour out your hearts before him</b> — the practice of personal lament as a recognized form of covenant speech. \"Pouring out\" the heart is the idiom for the unguarded expression of inner distress before YHWH (1 Sam 1:15 — Hannah \"poured out her soul\" before YHWH). The invitation is to the <i>people</i> collectively, not just individuals: communal lament was a recognized liturgical practice (Joel 1:14; 2:12-17; Lam 2:19). YHWH as \"a refuge for us\" (<i>maḥseh lanu</i>) is the covenant-guarantee that the lament is heard.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>Common people are only a breath / people of rank are a deception</b> — the two social categories: <i>benei adam</i> (sons of Adam = common people, the generic human being) and <i>benei ish</i> (sons of man = men of distinction, the aristocratic class). Both are weighed on scales and found lighter than a breath — the scales imagery is from Egypt's Hall of Judgment (weighing of the heart) but used here for YHWH's moral evaluation of all human pretension to power. The wisdom observation is genuinely egalitarian: wealth and rank fail the scale-test equally.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>Do not trust in extortion; do not take pride in robbery</b> — two specific economic crimes named: <i>ashaq</i> (oppression/extortion, the abuse of economic leverage) and <i>gazal</i> (robbery, violent seizure of property). These are the specific sins condemned in the prophets against exploiting the poor (Amos 4:1; Mic 2:2; Jer 22:13-17). \"If wealth increases, do not set your heart on it\" — the prohibition against heart-attachment to wealth echoes Deut 8:11-17 and anticipates Matt 6:21.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>God has spoken once; two things I have heard</b> — the \"once... twice\" (or X / X+1) numerical formula appears in wisdom poetry (Prov 6:16-19; 30:15-31; Job 33:14; Amos 1-2) as a rhetorical device emphasizing completeness and authority. The double hearing from a single divine speech underscores the certainty of what follows. In prophetic tradition, YHWH's word spoken once was sufficient and certain (Isa 55:10-11); the psalmist's \"twice\" represents the hearer's complete reception, not a deficiency in the divine utterance.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>Power belongs to God / and to you, O Lord, belongs steadfast love</b> — the pairing of <i>oz</i> (power/strength) and <i>hesed</i> (steadfast love/covenant loyalty) as the two divine attributes is the same pairing as in Ps 59:16-17. Power without love produces tyranny; love without power produces ineffectiveness. YHWH's governance of history combines both: the power to enforce and the loyalty to keep covenant. \"For you repay each person according to their deeds\" — the covenant guarantee that moral order is underwritten by the one who has both power and loyalty.</p>"
  },
  "63": {
    "1": "<p><b>When he was in the wilderness of Judah</b> — the superscription locates this psalm in a specific biographical moment. Two major wilderness periods fit: David's years fleeing Saul in the Judean desert around En-gedi and Maon (1 Sam 23-26), or his flight from Jerusalem during Absalom's revolt through the wilderness east of the city (2 Sam 15:23-16:14). The Judean wilderness — the harsh rain-shadow desert between Jerusalem and the Dead Sea — is the setting. The three-fold intensification (\"my soul thirsts... my flesh longs\") is the most physicalized expression of spiritual longing in the Psalter: spiritual hunger described in terms of dehydration and bodily craving.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>So I have gazed upon you in the sanctuary, beholding your power and your glory</b> — the sanctuary is the place where YHWH's <i>kavod</i> (glory/presence) was concentrated and visible. The Tabernacle (and later the Temple) was the architectural embodiment of this principle: YHWH's visible, experienceable presence was accessible in the sanctuary in a way it was not in the wilderness. The psalmist's thirst (v1) is partly resolved by <i>memory</i> of sanctuary encounter: even in the waterless wilderness, the remembered vision of divine glory sustains the soul.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>Your steadfast love is better than life itself</b> — this is among the most radical theological claims in the Psalter. In ancient Israelite thought, life (<i>hayyim</i>) was the highest good — everything in the covenant system (blessings, inheritance, descendants, health) was understood as fullness of life. To say that <i>hesed</i> (covenant loyalty) surpasses life itself is to place the covenant relationship above the life it sustains. This anticipates the NT's claim that to know God is eternal life (John 17:3) and Paul's \"to live is Christ and to die is gain\" (Phil 1:21).</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>In your name I will lift up my hands</b> — the physical posture of prayer with hands raised toward heaven was common across the ancient Near East. Egyptian, Mesopotamian, and Israelite prayer art all depict raised hands as the gesture of petition and devotion. Lifting hands toward the Name (<i>shem</i>) situates the prayer within the theology of divine presence mediated through YHWH's name: the name was understood as a real extension of his person, present in the sanctuary (Deut 12:11; 1 Kgs 8:29). Lifting hands toward the Name is lifting hands toward the dwelling of YHWH's effective presence.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>My soul is satisfied as with the richest of food</b> — the imagery of the <i>todah</i> (thanksgiving) banquet. When a worshiper's prayer was answered, they were expected to return to the temple with a <i>todah</i> sacrifice; the offering included leavened bread, and the meat was eaten at a communal meal with invited guests (Ps 22:26; Lev 7:11-15). \"The richest of food\" (<i>chelev vadeshen</i>, fat and abundance) describes the quality of this sacred meal. The psalmist's spiritual satisfaction in the wilderness is imagined in terms of the fellowship meal of answered prayer that awaits in the sanctuary.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>I meditate on you through the watches of the night</b> — the ancient Israelite night was divided into three watches (Judg 7:19: beginning of the middle watch; Lam 2:19: beginning of the night watches; Exod 14:24: the morning watch). Later, Roman military practice introduced four watches, which the NT uses (Mark 13:35). The Psalter frequently locates the most intense divine encounters in the night hours (Ps 16:7; 17:3; 42:8; 119:62). Night meditation on YHWH was both a devotional practice and a practical necessity in the heat of the Judean wilderness.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>In the shadow of your wings I will rejoice</b> — the wings imagery has a dual referent in Israelite theology: (1) the cherubim of the ark of the covenant, whose outstretched wings formed YHWH's throne (Exod 25:20; 1 Chr 28:18; Ps 80:1; 99:1); and (2) the mother-bird imagery of divine protection (Deut 32:11 — \"like an eagle that stirs up its nest and hovers over its young\"; Ps 91:4). Both images speak to the protective presence of YHWH: under the wings of the cherubim-throne, and sheltered by the mother-bird of Deut 32. In the wilderness, away from the ark, the psalmist claims that protection as still available.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>My soul clings close to you</b> — the verb <i>dabaq</i> (to cling, cleave, hold fast) is the specific covenant-loyalty verb of Deuteronomy. Deut 10:20: \"Fear the LORD your God and <i>dabaq</i> to him\"; Deut 11:22: \"to <i>dabaq</i> to him\"; Deut 30:20: \"<i>dabaq</i> to him — for he is your life.\" This is the same verb used in Gen 2:24 for the husband's bond to his wife. The psalmist describes his relationship with YHWH in the wilderness using the covenant-loyalty language of Deuteronomy: not sentiment but the formal, embodied attachment of the covenant partner who refuses to let go.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>Those who seek to destroy my life shall descend into the depths of the earth</b> — \"the lower parts of the earth\" (<i>tahtiyyot ha-aretz</i>) is Sheol, the underworld realm of the dead (Ezek 26:20; 31:14-18; 32:18-32 use the same phrase for descent to the underworld). In ancient Israelite cosmology, the earth had three levels: the heavens above, the earth's surface, and Sheol beneath. Those who threaten the psalmist's life will themselves go where life ceases — the reversal of fate is a consistent pattern in the lament psalms (Ps 7:15-16; 35:8; 57:6).</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>They will be delivered over to the sword; they will become prey for jackals</b> — the shame of unburied death. In the ancient world, proper burial was a fundamental requirement of social dignity; to be left unburied and consumed by scavengers was the ultimate humiliation (1 Sam 17:44-46 — Goliath's threat; Jer 7:33; 8:2; 16:4). Jackals (<i>shualim</i>) were the familiar scavengers of the Palestinian landscape, associated with desolation and the aftermath of judgment. The enemies who threatened the psalmist's life will suffer the most disgraceful possible end: no burial, no memorial, consumed by animals.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>The king will rejoice in God / the mouths of liars will be silenced</b> — the royal dimension surfaces at the psalm's close. The \"king\" is either David himself (if the psalm is autobiographical) or the Davidic king as the representative of the covenant community. His vindication by God produces joy (<i>yismaḥ</i>). \"All who swear by him will boast in him\" places the king's vindication within the community's covenant oath-structure: those who have sworn their loyalty to YHWH will share in the vindication. The silencing of liars completes the reversal: the double-speaking enemies of v4 find their mouths closed.</p>"
  },
  "64": {
    "1": "<p><b>Guard my life from the terror of the enemy</b> — the \"terror\" (<i>pahad</i>) here is specifically psychological: the dread produced by sustained enemy threat. This is not a battlefield situation but a social one — the fear of what conspirators may do. <i>Pahad</i> appears in the prophets as the paralyzing dread that overtakes those who know enemies are planning against them (Isa 24:17-18; Jer 20:3-4). The psalmist asks for protection specifically from the emotional and psychological weight of the threat, not only from its physical consequences.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>Shelter me from the conspiracy of the wicked</b> — the key word is <i>sod</i> (secret counsel, conspiracy). This is the same word used for the divine council: the assembly of heavenly beings who deliberate with YHWH (Ps 89:7; Jer 23:18, 22; Job 15:8; Amos 3:7). The wicked have their own conspiratorial \"council\" that parodies the divine assembly — a secret gathering that plots against the innocent just as the heavenly council deliberates over the fate of nations. The psalmist implicitly appeals to the true <i>sod</i> (the divine council) to protect him from the false one.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>They sharpen their tongues like swords and aim bitter words like arrows</b> — the tongue-as-weapon metaphor is pervasive in the wisdom tradition (Prov 12:18: \"reckless words pierce like a sword\"; 25:18: \"a false witness against a neighbor is a club, a sword, a sharp arrow\"; Jer 9:8: \"their tongue is a deadly arrow\"). In the social world of the ancient court, verbal attacks — slander, false accusation, poisonous rumors — could be as lethal as physical assault. Legal and social ruin followed from well-placed false accusations, making the tongue genuinely dangerous.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>Shooting from hiding places at the innocent; they strike suddenly and without fear</b> — the method of cowardly attack: the ambush, the sudden strike, anonymity as cover. In ancient warfare, ambush was considered less honorable than open battle, because it did not give the opponent the chance to prepare or defend. The wicked's method reveals their character: they cannot defeat the innocent in open confrontation and so resort to stealth. \"Without fear\" — they act with impunity because they believe they are invisible (v5: \"who will see us?\").</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>Who will see us?</b> — the assumption that secret plots escape divine notice is the practical atheism of the Psalter's wicked. Ps 94:7 articulates the same folly: \"The LORD does not see; the God of Jacob does not perceive.\" The wicked function as practical atheists not by denying YHWH's existence but by behaving as though his perception is limited. This is the same error condemned in Ezek 8:12, where the elders of Israel say \"The LORD does not see us; the LORD has forsaken the land\" while conducting idolatrous worship in the dark.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>The inward thought and heart of a person are unfathomable</b> — a wisdom observation about the depth of human self-deception. Jer 17:9: \"The heart is deceitful above all things and beyond cure — who can understand it?\" The wicked's \"perfect scheme\" is self-assessed; they cannot see the depths of their own wickedness because the heart that generates the scheme is the same heart evaluating it. The irony is that they call their plan \"complete\" (<i>tamam</i>) — the same word used for blamelessness before YHWH — while it is in fact morally corrupt to its depths.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>But God will shoot his arrow at them; suddenly they will be struck down</b> — the divine reversal uses the same weapon the wicked used: arrows (vv 3-4). The lex talionis structure is not incidental — what the wicked aimed at the innocent comes back on them through divine action. This is the consistent moral grammar of the Psalter's justice: the pit the wicked dig for others they fall into themselves (Ps 7:15-16; 9:15-16; 35:8; 57:6). The divine arrow is \"sudden\" (<i>pitom</i>) — the same unexpected quality that characterized the wicked's own attack (v4).</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>God makes their own tongues their undoing</b> — the precise reversal of v3: they sharpened their tongues like swords; their tongues become the instrument of their own destruction. The mechanism is not explained — the point is the structural justice. This reversal-of-weapon pattern appears in Esther (Haman hanged on the gallows he built for Mordecai, Esth 7:10), in Proverbs (Prov 11:8; 26:27: \"the one who digs a pit falls into it\"), and most dramatically in the cross — the instrument of execution becomes the instrument of resurrection.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>Then all people will stand in fear; they will proclaim what God has done</b> — the public nature of divine judgment is essential to its function in covenant theology. YHWH's vindication of the innocent is not a private transaction; it is meant to be seen, declared, and pondered by the entire community. This is the social function of the <i>todah</i> (thanksgiving) ceremony: the rescued person publicly declares what God did so that the community's faith is renewed (Ps 22:22-31; 66:16; 107:21-22). Divine justice that is not publicly visible cannot function as a moral framework for society.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>The righteous will rejoice in the LORD and take refuge in him</b> — the psalm closes with the community's response to witnessed divine justice. \"Boasting\" in the LORD (<i>yithallal</i>) is the technical term for covenant-confident praise: Jer 9:23-24 explicitly prohibits boasting in wisdom, strength, or wealth and directs all boasting to knowing YHWH. The \"upright in heart\" — those whose inward reality matches their outward profession — are the contrast to the wicked whose inward thought was corrupt (v6). The division of humanity that underlies Psalm 1 (the righteous and the wicked) is the lens through which Psalm 64 resolves.</p>"
  },
  "65": {
    "1": "<p><b>Praise awaits you in silence, O God, in Zion</b> — this is a harvest thanksgiving psalm associated with Zion, possibly connected to one of the three annual pilgrimage festivals (Passover, Weeks/Shavuot, or Tabernacles/Sukkot — Deut 16:16). The agricultural thanksgiving of vv 9-13 best fits Shavuot (wheat harvest) or Tabernacles (the ingathering of all crops). The psalm bears both \"Psalm\" and \"Song\" designations. \"Vow shall be fulfilled\" (<i>yeshullam neder</i>) — the vow made in distress is publicly paid at the temple upon the prayer's answer.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>To you all flesh shall come</b> — the universality of prayer in Zion theology. While the Torah's cultic system specified who could enter which courts of the sanctuary, the prophets envisioned Zion as the prayer-destination of all peoples (Isa 56:7: \"my house shall be called a house of prayer for all peoples\"; Isa 2:2-4: \"all nations shall stream to it\"). \"All flesh\" (<i>kol-basar</i>) is the most comprehensive possible term for humanity, used in Gen 6-9 for all living creatures. YHWH who hears prayer is accessible to all humanity, not only to Israel's covenant members.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>When our sins overwhelm us, you atone for our transgressions</b> — the prerequisite for temple access is divine atonement for sin. The worshiper who comes to Zion carrying accumulated transgressions cannot simply enter the divine presence; atonement must precede access. This is the function of the sacrificial system and the Day of Atonement (Lev 16) in the priestly theology: YHWH provides the mechanism of atonement that makes his own presence accessible. The note here is entirely divine initiative — \"you atone\" (<i>tekhapper</i>), not the worshiper's self-purification.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>Blessed is the one you choose and bring near, to dwell in your courts</b> — the beatitude form used for divine election to temple access. In the priestly system, only Levites could serve in the sanctuary; the high priest alone could enter the Holy of Holies once per year. But the prophets expanded this theology: Isa 56:3-7 explicitly extends temple-access to foreigners and eunuchs who might have been excluded under some readings of the Torah. This verse's \"chosen and brought near\" anticipates that broader vision — the one YHWH selects for nearness is blessed regardless of prior status.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>You are the hope of all the ends of the earth and of the most distant seas</b> — the cosmic scope of YHWH's saving reach. \"The ends of the earth\" (<i>qetze ha-aretz</i>) and \"the most distant seas\" (<i>yam rehokkim</i>) are standard formulas for the geographic extremes of the known world. In the Second Temple period, Jewish diaspora communities stretched from Egypt to Babylon to Persia, and the question of YHWH's accessibility to dispersed Israel far from Zion was a live theological concern (Solomon's prayer in 1 Kgs 8:41-43 explicitly addresses foreigners and those who pray toward the temple from far away).</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>The one who by his strength sets the mountains in place, who is clothed with power</b> — the mountains as evidence of divine power over creation. In ANE cosmology, mountains were understood as the pillars supporting the vault of the sky (Job 26:11; Ps 75:3) and as the dwelling places of the gods (Baal's Mount Zaphon; YHWH's Mount Sinai and Zion). The God who \"sets\" the mountains in place — who established them at creation — is the same God who controls the agricultural cycle of vv 9-13. The psalm moves from cosmic creative power to the intimate detail of watering furrows.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>You still the roaring of the seas, the roaring of their waves, and the uproar of the nations</b> — the parallelism of the seas' roaring and the nations' tumult is not merely poetic. In ANE cosmology (and in Ps 2:1; 46:3; 93:3-4; Isa 17:12-13; Rev 17:15), the chaos-waters and the tumultuous nations are related symbols: both represent powers of disorder that oppose divine order. YHWH who controls the physical chaos of the storm-sea also governs the historical chaos of rebellious nations. Creation-theology and history-theology are one unified framework in the Psalter.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Those who live at earth's farthest bounds stand in awe of your signs</b> — the cosmic portents (<i>otot</i>, signs) that YHWH performs are visible to those at the geographic extremes. The concept of signs that produce <i>yirah</i> (fear/awe) at a distance is rooted in the Exodus tradition (the plagues as signs — Exod 10:1-2; the Rahab narrative — Josh 2:9-10, where those at a distance heard and were terrified). The phrase \"you make the sunrise and sunset ring with joy\" personifies the dawn and dusk as the boundaries of each day's divine proclamation.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>You visit the earth and water it abundantly; you enrich it with the river of God</b> — the rain cycle as covenant blessing and implicit Baal polemic. Baal was the Canaanite storm-and-rain deity; the entire Baal cult cycle was predicated on the claim that Baal's annual death and resurrection controlled the agricultural calendar. Ps 65's harvest thanksgiving attributes every element of the rain cycle to YHWH directly: he visits the earth, waters it, fills the channels, provides the grain. The \"river of God\" (<i>nahar elohim</i>) is the heavenly reservoir of water (Gen 1:6-8; Ps 104:13) from which YHWH draws to send rain. YHWH does what Baal's worshipers claimed Baal did.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>You soak its furrows abundantly, you level its ridges, you soften it with showers</b> — the agricultural detail is remarkable for its intimacy and specificity: furrows plowed for planting, ridges between rows, the softening rain that prepares the seedbed. The God who set the mountains in place (v6) also tends the individual furrow. This theological move — from cosmic creation-power to agricultural intimacy — is characteristic of the Psalter's creation theology (compare Ps 104, which moves from light and stars to the feeding of young ravens). YHWH is not an absentee cosmic deity but the intimate sustainer of the agricultural cycle.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>You crown the year with your bounty; your wagon tracks overflow with abundance</b> — the harvest is personified as YHWH's processional wagon, overflowing with grain as it passes. The image of YHWH's wagon-tracks dripping with fat abundance portrays the divine journey through the landscape as leaving behind a trail of fertility. This processional imagery connects to the Feast of Tabernacles and to the ark processions (Ps 68:7-8, 17-18), where YHWH's movement through the land brings blessing. The harvest is not an impersonal agricultural outcome but the aftermath of divine presence passing through.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>The pastures of the wilderness overflow; the hills are wrapped in rejoicing</b> — even the uninhabited wilderness areas (<i>midbar</i>) receive the divine bounty. The \"pastures of the wilderness\" are the steppe areas used for grazing flocks but not for agriculture; YHWH's blessing reaches beyond the cultivated farmland to the pastoral economy as well. \"The hills are wrapped in rejoicing\" (<i>gevot tachgornah</i>, the hills gird themselves with joy) — the imagery of hills putting on joy as a garment, personification that prepares for the full personification of the landscape in v13.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>The meadows are dressed with flocks; the valleys are blanketed with grain — they shout for joy, they break into song</b> — the entire landscape is personified as the worshipping community. The flocks clothing the meadows and grain blanketing the valleys are images of abundance so complete that the landscape itself joins the human festival. This personification of creation as a worshipping assembly connects to Ps 96:11-12 (\"let the heavens be glad, let the earth rejoice\") and to the eschatological vision of Isa 55:12 where \"the mountains and hills will burst into song before you and all the trees of the field will clap their hands.\"</p>"
  },
  "66": {
    "1": "<p><b>Shout joyfully to God, all the earth</b> — the opening imperative uses <i>hari'u</i>, the battle-shout of victory that doubles as the shout of liturgical celebration. In ancient Israel, the same word covered both the war-cry of advancing armies (Josh 6:5, 20 — the shout at Jericho) and the acclamatory shout of temple worship (Ps 47:1; 95:1-2; 98:4; 100:1). The addressees — \"all the earth\" (<i>kol ha-aretz</i>) — expand the typical Israelite worship community to the universal scope of all human beings and nations.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>Sing the glory of his name; make his praise resplendent</b> — name theology: the <i>shem</i> (name) of YHWH was not merely a title but the presence and personality of God made accessible. In ancient Near Eastern thought, the name of a god or king was a real extension of that being's power and identity. The Deuteronomic theology of \"the place where YHWH causes his name to dwell\" (Deut 12:11; 14:23; 16:6) placed the divine name — and therefore the divine presence — in the sanctuary. Singing \"the glory of his name\" is praising the presence that the name makes available.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>Through the greatness of your power your enemies cower before you</b> — the submission (<i>yikahash</i>, literally \"cringe/feign submission\") of enemies before YHWH's power is a standard theme in ANE royal ideology: the great king's power was demonstrated by the submission of vassal states and defeated enemies. Egyptian royal art regularly depicted foreign enemies prostrating before Pharaoh; Assyrian reliefs showed defeated kings kissing the feet of the victor. Here the submission is directed not to a human king but to YHWH — universal political submission transferred to the divine sovereign.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>All the earth bows down before you; they sing to you, they sing praises to your name</b> — the universal worship anticipated in v1 is described as accomplished fact. The shift from imperative (v1: \"shout!\") to declarative (v4: \"all the earth bows\") creates the liturgical tension characteristic of these psalms: the worshipping community calls the world to what they simultaneously proclaim is already the truth about YHWH's sovereignty. This is the \"already/not yet\" structure of covenant eschatology — the truth is declared before it is universally visible.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>Come and see what God has done; he is awesome in his acts toward humanity</b> — the \"come and see\" (<i>lekhu ure'u</i>) is a liturgical invitation to communal witness. It appears in Ps 46:8 (\"Come, behold the works of the LORD\") and reflects the practice of gathering the community to observe or hear about divine actions. The psalm invites both the Israelite congregation and, by implication, the nations (addressed in vv 1-4) to observe the specific acts recounted in vv 6-12. \"Awesome in his acts toward humanity\" (<i>nora alilah al benei adam</i>) frames these acts as universally significant.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>He turned the sea into dry land; they crossed the river on foot; there we rejoiced in him</b> — a dual Exodus allusion: \"the sea\" is the Reed Sea crossing (Exod 14:21-22), and \"the river\" may be the Jordan crossing under Joshua (Josh 3:14-17) or also the Reed Sea (Exod 15:19). The \"we\" is remarkable: the psalmist identifies with both crossings across centuries. This is the liturgical participation in history characteristic of Passover — the Haggadah's \"in every generation, each person is obligated to see themselves as if they personally went out from Egypt.\" Israel's historical memory is corporate and participatory.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>He rules by his power forever; his eyes watch over the nations</b> — from the specific historical events of vv 5-6 (the Exodus/Jordan crossings), the psalm moves to the abiding truth they demonstrate: YHWH's eternal governance over all nations. \"His eyes watch over the nations\" (<i>einav ba-goyim titzpennah</i>) — the divine watchfulness that the wicked in Ps 64:5 assumed was absent (\"who will see us?\") is here asserted as permanent and universal. The nations who bow in v4 are watched by the eyes of the God who rules forever.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Bless our God, O peoples; let the sound of his praise be heard</b> — the second imperative to the nations, framed as an audible proclamation: the praise should resound so that it can be heard at a distance. In ancient worship settings, the sound of the congregation's worship was itself theologically significant: the great shout of Ps 47:1; 95:1 was understood to have cosmic weight. The invitation to the <i>peoples</i> (<i>ammim</i>) to bless the God identified as \"our God\" (<i>elohenu</i>) maintains the tension between YHWH's universal sovereignty and Israel's covenant particularity.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>He keeps our lives from death and does not allow our feet to stumble</b> — the preservation of life as the ongoing divine action. The specific expression \"keeps us in life\" (<i>hassam nafshenu ba-hayyim</i>) is the covenant guarantee of survival and flourishing. \"Not allowing our feet to stumble\" echoes Ps 121:3 (\"he will not let your foot slip — he who watches over you will not slumber\"). The divine preservation is continuous and habitual — not a single rescue but an ongoing sustaining action that accounts for the community's very existence from day to day.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>You have tested us; you have refined us as silver is refined</b> — the refining of silver as an image for divine testing through affliction. The process: silver ore was heated until the metal liquefied and the dross (impurities) floated to the surface where they could be skimmed off, leaving increasingly pure silver. This image appears in Isa 48:10 (\"I have refined you... I have tested you in the furnace of affliction\"), Mal 3:2-3 (the Lord as a refiner's fire), Prov 17:3 (\"the crucible is for silver and the furnace for gold, but the LORD tests the heart\"), and Zech 13:9. The covenant community's suffering is framed as a divine refining process, not as abandonment.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>You brought us into the net; you laid a crushing burden on our backs</b> — the net (<i>metzudah</i>) was used for catching fish and birds — the trapped creature that cannot escape. These images describe national catastrophe — possibly the Egyptian bondage, the Babylonian exile, or a specific military defeat — as the experience of being caught in a trap by God himself. The suffering is not chaotic but purposeful: YHWH set the net for the refining of vv 10-12. The specific identification of YHWH as the one who brought them into trouble is characteristic of Israel's honest theodicy.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>We went through fire and through water; yet you brought us out to a spacious place</b> — fire and water as the two elemental tests. In the Exodus framework: the pillar of fire (Exod 13:21-22; 14:24) and the waters of the sea and wilderness (Exod 14:21-22; 15:22-27; 17:1-7). Isaiah 43:2 brings both together as covenant promises: \"When you pass through the waters... when you walk through fire.\" The \"spacious place\" (<i>la-revayah</i>) echoes Ps 18:19 and 31:8 — the rescue brings the one trapped in narrow distress into open space.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>I will come into your house with burnt offerings; I will fulfill my vows to you</b> — the psalm shifts from corporate \"we\" (vv 1-12) to individual \"I\" (vv 13-20), marking the transition from community praise to individual <i>todah</i>. The individual todah (thanksgiving) ceremony was one of the most important elements of Israelite worship. When prayer was answered, the worshiper was obligated to return to the temple with the offering vowed in distress (Lev 7:11-15; Ps 50:14; 56:12; 116:13-14, 17-18). The entire congregation would gather to witness the vow fulfillment; the sacrificial meal would be shared with invited guests.</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>The vows that my lips uttered and my mouth spoke in my time of trouble</b> — the explicit reminder that these vows were made under duress, not in prosperity. ANE vow-making was common practice: in crisis, one would promise a sacrifice or gift to the deity if the prayer were answered. The Israelite practice was formalized but the psychology was the same. What distinguished the Israelite <i>todah</i> from merely fulfilling a transactional obligation was the public testimony (vv 16-17): the rescued person declared what God had done, making the fulfillment an act of witness, not merely debt payment.</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>I will offer you burnt offerings of fattened animals, with the rising smoke of rams</b> — the specific offerings enumerated: fattened animals, rams, bulls, and goats. The quality of the offerings signals the magnitude of the deliverance being celebrated: fattened animals were the premium offering, more valuable than ordinary livestock. The ascending smoke (<i>mektar</i>, incense/smoke of offering) was understood as the pleasing aroma that reached the divine presence (Gen 8:21; Lev 1:9), signaling the worshiper's intent to communicate gratitude upward to YHWH.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>Come and hear, all you who fear God, and I will tell what he has done for me</b> — the public testimony component of the <i>todah</i> ceremony. The rescued person invited the assembled community to hear their declaration; this was the \"witness\" function of the thanksgiving service. \"All you who fear God\" (<i>yirei elohim</i>) — the theologically precise audience: those who already stand in covenant relationship with YHWH. In Acts 10:2, 22 and 13:16, 26, <i>phoboumenoi ton theon</i> (God-fearers) is the technical term for Gentile adherents to Judaism — the psalmist's phrase may have been the precedent for that terminology.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>I cried out to him with my mouth, and his praise was on my tongue</b> — the sequence: petition first, then praise. The praise was on the tongue even as the cry went up — not as chronological sequence but as the characteristic of covenant prayer that begins with YHWH's character (his praise-worthiness) before stating the need. The Psalter's consistent prayer-pedagogy: lament psalms consistently open or close with praise that frames the petition within YHWH's covenant faithfulness. The praise was not the result of the answer but the stance from which the prayer was offered.</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>If I had cherished sin in my heart, the Lord would not have listened</b> — the prerequisite of inner integrity for answered prayer. \"Cherished sin in my heart\" (<i>avon ra'iti belibbi</i>) — the moral of <i>looking at/regarding</i> iniquity (holding it in view, entertaining it, nursing it). This is not a claim of sinlessness but of not harboring deliberate, cherished sin. The same principle appears in Isa 59:2 (\"your iniquities have separated you from your God\"), Prov 28:9 (\"if anyone turns a deaf ear to my instruction, even their prayers are detestable\"), and 1 Pet 3:12.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>But truly God has heard; he has attended to the voice of my prayer</b> — the declaration of answered prayer that forms the climax of the individual <i>todah</i> testimony. \"Attended to\" (<i>hiqshiv</i>) — to prick up the ears, to listen carefully, to give attentive care. The word is used in Prov 4:1 for a father attending to his son's instruction. The emphasis on both hearing (<i>shama</i>) and attending (<i>hiqshiv</i>) is emphatic by redundancy: not only did YHWH hear but he leaned in, he paid close attention to this specific prayer.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>Blessed be God, who has not turned away my prayer or withheld his steadfast love from me</b> — the closing doxology frames the entire psalm's movement. The \"blessing\" of God by humans (<i>baruk elohim</i>) is the covenant response to answered prayer — humans \"bless\" YHWH by declaring his worth and faithfulness publicly. The two things YHWH did not withhold — the prayer's answer and his <i>hesed</i> (covenant loyalty) — are the same pairing as in Ps 62:12 (power and hesed). The psalm that opened with \"all the earth\" shouting to God (v1) closes with one person blessing God for <i>hesed</i> extended specifically to them.</p>"
  },
  "67": {
    "1": "<p><b>May God be gracious to us and bless us, and may he cause his face to shine upon us</b> — Psalm 67 deliberately echoes the Aaronic blessing of Num 6:24-26 (\"The LORD bless you and keep you; the LORD make his face shine on you and be gracious to you; the LORD turn his face toward you and give you peace\"). The connection is not incidental — nearly every phrase of Ps 67:1 draws from the Num 6 blessing. The significance: what was originally a priestly blessing pronounced over Israel is here turned into a prayer that Israel's blessing might have a missionary purpose. The Aaronic blessing was the beginning of a chain of blessing running outward to all nations.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>So that your way may be known on earth, your saving power among all the nations</b> — the purpose clause that makes this the Psalter's most explicit missiological text. The blessing of Israel in v1 is explicitly instrumentalized: <i>not</i> so that Israel alone may flourish, but so that YHWH's way (<i>darkekha</i>) and his saving power (<i>yeshuatekha</i>) may be known among all nations. This purpose-structure echoes the original Abrahamic promise: \"all peoples on earth will be blessed through you\" (Gen 12:3). Israel's particular blessing exists for the universal goal — a principle the NT applies to the church as Abraham's heirs (Gal 3:8-9, 14).</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>Let the peoples praise you, O God; let all the peoples give you praise</b> — the first occurrence of the refrain that divides the psalm's three stanzas (vv 1-3, 4-5, 6-7). The refrain is imperative: \"Let the peoples praise\" — it is a call to universal worship, not merely a prediction. <i>Ammim</i> (peoples/nations) in the plural is the standard term for non-Israelite nations. The universal scope is total: \"all the peoples\" (<i>kol ha-ammim</i>). The refrain was likely sung by the assembled congregation as a response between the leader's verses.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>For you will judge the peoples with fairness, and guide the nations of the earth</b> — the theological ground for universal praise: YHWH is the judge of all nations, not merely Israel's patron deity. \"Judge with fairness\" (<i>tishpot ammim mishor</i>) — <i>mishor</i> (uprightness, equity, a level surface) is the quality of unbiased judicial process. The same claim appears in Ps 9:8; 96:10; 98:9; and Isa 2:4 (YHWH judging between nations, settling disputes). \"Guide the nations\" (<i>leummim ba-aretz tanhem</i>) — YHWH as the shepherd-guide of all peoples, not merely Israel. This is the basis on which all nations should rejoice and praise.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>Let the peoples praise you, O God; let all the peoples give you praise</b> — the refrain appears for the second time at the structural center of the psalm. In the MT, Ps 67 has seven verses; the refrain at vv 3 and 5 creates a chiastic structure with v4 at the center (the universality of YHWH's just governance) and vv 6-7 as the final movement. The Qumran community (11QPsa) preserved this psalm alongside Ps 68, suggesting it was used as a liturgical connector. The doubled refrain marks the psalm's central affirmation.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>The earth has given its harvest; God, our own God, has blessed us</b> — the harvest as evidence of divine blessing. The statement \"God, our own God\" (<i>elohim elohenu</i>) is striking: the God who judges all nations (v4) and before whom all peoples should praise (vv 3, 5) is also \"our own God\" — the covenant God who has a particular relationship with Israel. This covenant particularity is not a contradiction of the universal vision; it is the mechanism of it. YHWH blesses Israel as the concrete, historical demonstration of his universal lordship, so that all ends of the earth may see and fear (v7).</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>God blesses us, and all the ends of the earth will stand in awe of him</b> — the closing verse completes the chain: the Aaronic blessing (v1) → the missionary purpose (v2) → the call to universal praise (vv 3, 5) → the harvest evidence (v6) → the universal fear/awe that results (v7). \"All the ends of the earth will stand in awe\" (<i>yeiru oto kol afsei aretz</i>) — <i>yare</i> (fear/awe/reverence) in this context is not terror but the reverent recognition of divine sovereignty that prompts worship. The psalm's movement from \"grace us and bless us\" (v1) to \"all the ends of the earth will fear him\" (v7) is the complete arc of the Abrahamic covenant's missiological vision.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 22 is the most cited OT Psalm in the NT Passion narratives. Its historical background (David's persecution?) is unknown — the Psalm presents an archetypal experience of abandonment and vindication. The pattern: intense lament (vv. 1-21) → sudden transition to praise (v. 22) → eschatological proclamation (vv. 27-31: 'all the families of the nations shall worship before you ... posterity shall serve him; it shall be told of the Lord to the coming generation'). The Psalm functions in NT usage not as a prediction of specific details but as the divinely-given interpretive framework for understanding the cross: suffering-unto-vindication, abandonment-unto-universal-proclamation.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 110 is the most frequently quoted OT text in the NT. Jesus cites it in the Synoptics (Matt 22:41-46 and parallels) as a riddle about the Messiah's nature. Peter cites it at Pentecost (Acts 2:34-35). Paul cites it (1 Cor 15:25; Eph 1:20; Col 3:1). Hebrews cites or alludes to it eight times (1:3, 13; 5:6, 10; 6:20; 7:17, 21; 8:1; 10:12-13). Its dominance in NT Christology is due to its dual claim: (1) divine enthronement at God's right hand; (2) eternal Melchizedekian priesthood. These two — divine lordship and perfect priesthood — are the two Christological pillars the NT builds on from this one Psalm.</p>"
  }
}

PSA_CHRIST = {
  "2": {
    "7": "<p>A direct revelation: 'You are my Son; today I have begotten you.' The royal Psalm 2 reaches its Christological fullness in the resurrection. Paul at Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:33): God raised Jesus, 'as it is written in the second Psalm, You are my Son, today I have begotten you.' The 'today' of divine fatherhood is not the eternal generation alone but the specific day of the resurrection-enthronement, when the Son's identity is publicly declared. Every application of Ps 2:7 in the NT (baptism, transfiguration, resurrection) marks a moment when the Father publicly declares the Son's identity for the community to hear.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>A fulfillment: 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?' The Passion Psalm that Jesus cited from the cross is both a historical lament (David in extremity) and a Christological prophecy (the Son's abandonment in the atonement). The cry 'why have you forsaken me' is not a failure of faith but a genuine experience of divine absence — the moment when Christ bore the full weight of human sin-under-judgment. The Psalm's movement (dereliction → trust → vindication → universal proclamation) is the death-and-resurrection narrative in miniature. Jesus did not die in despair; the Psalm he cited ends in the world's worship of YHWH through the one who suffered.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The LORD says to my Lord: Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool.' The most foundational Christological oracle in the OT: the risen and ascended Christ is enthroned at the Father's right hand (the supreme position of divine authority) awaiting the final subjection of all enemies, including death (1 Cor 15:25-26). The present era is the era of Christ's enthronement: he reigns now, his enemies are being progressively placed under his feet, and the ultimate subjection is certain. Ps 110:1 frames the entire NT's understanding of the ascension and the present Christological situation of the cosmos.</p>",

    "4": "<p>A fulfillment: 'You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek.' The divine oath of the eternal priesthood is fulfilled in Christ's resurrection, which established him as the priest who never dies. Unlike the Levitical priests who needed to offer sacrifice repeatedly and who were replaced by death, Christ offered himself once and lives forever in the power of an indestructible life (Heb 7:16, 24-25). The Melchizedekian priesthood — prior to Aaron, not from the tribe of Levi, without recorded end — is the OT's own signal that the Levitical system was provisional. Christ's eternal intercession ('he always lives to make intercession for them', Heb 7:25) is the fulfillment of Ps 110:4's oath.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('psalms')
    merge_echo(e, PSA_ECHO)
    save_echo('psalms', e)
    print(f'Psalms echo: {len(e)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in e.values())} verses')

